27
00:02:12,415 --> 00:02:19,798
How we tried to reinvent brainstorming and a typical conception process to come up with

28
00:02:19,818 --> 00:02:20,799
the IP in the first place.

29
00:02:21,979 --> 00:02:27,823
How we had some stumbles along the way as we tried to grow and expand that process.

30
00:02:28,744 --> 00:02:37,650
And then how we had to regain our footing and re-find our balance to close out production and really bring everything back together.

31
00:02:38,871 --> 00:02:45,236
But first I want to start with the fun and terrifying part of starting a new IP, which is the conception phase.

32
00:02:46,548 --> 00:02:50,256
And in order to tell this story, I've got to go way, way, way back to the beginning of the story,

33
00:02:51,439 --> 00:02:55,989
which is the ending of another story of Splinter Cell Blacklist.

34
00:02:58,370 --> 00:03:02,913
Splinter Cell Blacklist was the first project from the Ubisoft Toronto studio, and at the

35
00:03:02,933 --> 00:03:06,296
time everyone at the studio had been working together to ship it.

36
00:03:07,117 --> 00:03:11,721
And I had joined Ubisoft Toronto during the production of Blacklist, and we worked through

37
00:03:11,741 --> 00:03:14,403
that and brought that to a close.

38
00:03:14,863 --> 00:03:20,067
And at the end of that project, as with many studios, people start splitting up and going

39
00:03:20,788 --> 00:03:21,609
on to separate things.

40
00:03:21,729 --> 00:03:26,593
And particularly at Toronto, we went from one project to lots of projects really quick.

41
00:03:27,153 --> 00:03:40,341
And since then, Toronto has been, has done many very successful collaborations on Far Cry Primal, Far Cry 4, Far Cry 5, Watch Dogs 2, Assassin's Creed Unity, you know, many of Ubisoft's biggest brands.

42
00:03:41,002 --> 00:03:46,605
But at the time, we also were given a chance to try something new and crazy.

43
00:03:47,386 --> 00:03:54,570
And I'm still not sure exactly how I lucked out and got this opportunity, but I was given the opportunity to take a very small group of people.

44
00:03:56,224 --> 00:03:59,505
And we were given this mandate, it looked like this,

45
00:04:01,726 --> 00:04:04,587
to basically come up with something new.

46
00:04:06,107 --> 00:04:09,868
And as far as mandates go, this one was really wide open.

47
00:04:11,149 --> 00:04:15,130
You know, explore innovative gameplay and next-gen hardware,

48
00:04:15,170 --> 00:04:17,651
which at the time meant Xbox One and PS4,

49
00:04:19,211 --> 00:04:21,432
with the goal of creating a mainstream concept for development.

50
00:04:22,432 --> 00:04:22,633
So...

51
00:04:24,155 --> 00:04:32,457
This is really a blank slate, and this kind of freedom is incredibly liberating and incredibly

52
00:04:32,517 --> 00:04:39,239
terrifying because it is super, super challenging to know where to go, especially with very

53
00:04:39,299 --> 00:04:43,540
limited resources when you have just this wide open space ahead of you.

54
00:04:45,420 --> 00:04:46,661
So we formed a little...

55
00:04:48,850 --> 00:04:52,053
prototyping group that we called Tomcat, I don't know why.

56
00:04:53,654 --> 00:04:55,255
And it was eight people to start.

57
00:04:56,436 --> 00:05:02,861
Two artists, two programmers, two game designers, one animator, and a manager.

58
00:05:05,639 --> 00:05:09,161
At this point I need to give a huge shout out. At the time we had two leads.

59
00:05:09,821 --> 00:05:14,844
So it was myself, I was the manager, and we had a lead designer named James Everett. And he and I

60
00:05:15,464 --> 00:05:20,206
really worked very closely together to come up with this process. So a huge shout out to him. He can't be here today, but

61
00:05:21,367 --> 00:05:23,408
we worked really closely together on this process.

62
00:05:25,850 --> 00:05:31,373
So we had this group of people, and these were a wonderful group of people who I thoroughly

63
00:05:31,413 --> 00:05:36,096
enjoyed working with, but to be fair, we were kind of the island of misfit toys.

64
00:05:38,777 --> 00:05:40,438
This was a group of people that...

65
00:05:41,433 --> 00:05:44,394
You know, when all of the project selection and things came up,

66
00:05:44,434 --> 00:05:47,315
and they were like, okay, do you want to work on, you know, the next big Far Cry thing,

67
00:05:47,355 --> 00:05:49,916
or, you know, the next Assassin's Creed, or whatever it was.

68
00:05:51,216 --> 00:05:53,997
These were the group of people that, you know, went dashing into the unknown,

69
00:05:54,797 --> 00:05:58,038
and said, I want to do the thing that's called Tomcat, but otherwise we know nothing about.

70
00:05:59,599 --> 00:06:04,343
And so, you know, it's a group of people that participated in a lot of game jams.

71
00:06:05,604 --> 00:06:09,547
You know, we're really attracted by coming up with brand new things and iterating on that.

72
00:06:10,989 --> 00:06:14,291
But it was also a group of people that really, you know, in many ways wanted to rebel

73
00:06:14,772 --> 00:06:18,135
against the standard structure and process and way that we do things,

74
00:06:18,875 --> 00:06:19,816
and way that things happen.

75
00:06:20,136 --> 00:06:24,300
And so, you know, we wanted to just reinvent everything, tear up all the rules and do something crazy.

76
00:06:26,897 --> 00:06:28,718
So we looked at how we would traditionally

77
00:06:28,758 --> 00:06:31,819
go about coming up with a new IP as a starting point.

78
00:06:31,839 --> 00:06:34,319
So we'd say, OK, well, we've got a bunch of people,

79
00:06:34,659 --> 00:06:36,040
any people, so we'll all get in a room.

80
00:06:36,060 --> 00:06:37,260
We'll brainstorm tons of ideas.

81
00:06:37,280 --> 00:06:38,441
We'll put stuff up on the wall.

82
00:06:39,761 --> 00:06:46,743
And then we'll all try to pick, or the leads will try to pick.

83
00:06:47,023 --> 00:06:48,444
And we'll say, this is the best idea.

84
00:06:48,684 --> 00:06:49,184
Let's do that.

85
00:06:50,164 --> 00:06:51,084
We build a demo out of it.

86
00:06:51,324 --> 00:06:53,665
And we polish that up and bring that to Paris and pitch it.

87
00:06:53,685 --> 00:06:54,365
It'll be amazing.

88
00:06:55,165 --> 00:06:55,706
It'll be awesome.

89
00:06:56,246 --> 00:06:56,566
High five.

90
00:06:58,870 --> 00:07:02,734
But when we looked at this process and the initial expectation,

91
00:07:03,936 --> 00:07:07,180
we had four big problems that we saw,

92
00:07:08,281 --> 00:07:10,984
that we didn't like about how this typical process works.

93
00:07:12,646 --> 00:07:17,492
The first, we all kind of hated brainstorming.

94
00:07:18,754 --> 00:07:19,795
In a traditional sense.

95
00:07:20,476 --> 00:07:22,698
And one of the big problems that we have with brainstorming

96
00:07:23,599 --> 00:07:27,543
is this effect of the loudest people in the room

97
00:07:28,043 --> 00:07:29,865
and the loudest ideas resonating.

98
00:07:30,065 --> 00:07:31,467
Not necessarily the best ideas.

99
00:07:32,087 --> 00:07:34,130
Typically if you throw ten people in a room,

100
00:07:34,170 --> 00:07:35,771
you say, okay, we're going to brainstorm this new thing.

101
00:07:36,732 --> 00:07:39,415
Everyone gets talking and, you know,

102
00:07:40,055 --> 00:07:44,277
You immediately start filtering down to three or four voices that are dominating this conversation,

103
00:07:44,738 --> 00:07:46,338
and the ideas are mostly coming from them.

104
00:07:46,958 --> 00:07:52,421
And there's a lot of people that have wonderful ideas that are going unheard because they're

105
00:07:52,961 --> 00:07:58,444
being spoken over or they can't get the word in, or they're not comfortable jumping into

106
00:07:58,484 --> 00:07:59,004
that fray.

107
00:08:01,225 --> 00:08:02,005
The second problem...

108
00:08:02,980 --> 00:08:03,941
It's biased selection.

109
00:08:04,541 --> 00:08:05,822
I've got two young kids right now.

110
00:08:06,683 --> 00:08:10,846
And with two young kids, there's always these events

111
00:08:10,906 --> 00:08:12,627
and holidays and things that roll around.

112
00:08:13,467 --> 00:08:18,030
And you get a lot of these best dad in the world things.

113
00:08:18,110 --> 00:08:20,412
And I think I'm a pretty good dad.

114
00:08:21,473 --> 00:08:25,395
But statistically, best dad in the world

115
00:08:25,435 --> 00:08:26,296
is probably a stretch.

116
00:08:27,256 --> 00:08:31,639
And we had similar worries with

117
00:08:33,259 --> 00:08:41,584
Our, James and I, you know, in a leadership role, with our biases affecting this process,

118
00:08:41,964 --> 00:08:45,607
where if we were going in and ideas are cropping up and people are throwing stuff on the wall,

119
00:08:46,347 --> 00:08:55,152
you know, we come from a very, you know, James and I both had kind of similar perspectives

120
00:08:55,233 --> 00:09:02,257
and similar interests, similar enough, you know, we came from similar backgrounds, and

121
00:09:03,592 --> 00:09:11,858
You know, looking at that, we were really worried that this wasn't necessarily going to be the idea that resonated with a wider audience.

122
00:09:11,878 --> 00:09:21,584
You know, the ideas that resonated to kind of two 30-something white guys who grew up in Canada would give us a fairly limited perspective and a limited selection.

123
00:09:22,905 --> 00:09:23,565
The third problem.

124
00:09:24,878 --> 00:09:25,779
Sounded good on paper.

125
00:09:25,799 --> 00:09:31,387
Okay, big caveat, I do not want to insult any game designers out there.

126
00:09:31,407 --> 00:09:32,689
I love game designers.

127
00:09:34,011 --> 00:09:38,377
But I think the best game designers...

128
00:09:39,909 --> 00:09:42,310
are kind of like the best batters in baseball, right?

129
00:09:43,150 --> 00:09:46,632
And when you write a pitch on paper, you write a design down,

130
00:09:46,652 --> 00:09:48,473
and you're like, okay, this is how this feature's gonna work,

131
00:09:48,513 --> 00:09:49,273
it's gonna be amazing,

132
00:09:50,474 --> 00:09:54,356
the best designers are probably batting at, you know,

133
00:09:54,556 --> 00:09:57,437
a 40% success rate of that idea actually translating

134
00:09:57,477 --> 00:09:59,559
into something that's really compelling and fun when you make it.

135
00:09:59,959 --> 00:10:03,000
And more often than not, you know, once you take that design

136
00:10:03,040 --> 00:10:05,081
that sounded great on paper and make it into...

137
00:10:05,962 --> 00:10:09,025
A game, and you spend, you know, the months developing that feature,

138
00:10:09,486 --> 00:10:12,489
you come back to it and you say, oh yeah, actually, we have to change that,

139
00:10:12,529 --> 00:10:14,872
it was kind of flawed, or didn't work exactly as we expected.

140
00:10:16,614 --> 00:10:18,696
And the fourth problem, which takes a little bit of explanation,

141
00:10:19,057 --> 00:10:20,358
something called the secretary problem.

142
00:10:20,378 --> 00:10:21,700
Quick show of hands, does anyone know what this...

143
00:10:22,526 --> 00:10:24,528
Means, does anyone know what this is?

144
00:10:25,009 --> 00:10:25,429
Navi knows.

145
00:10:27,312 --> 00:10:30,255
So the secretary problem is a mathematical problem

146
00:10:31,497 --> 00:10:32,678
with a kind of dated name.

147
00:10:33,839 --> 00:10:37,544
And the secretary problem speaks to the challenge of

148
00:10:38,965 --> 00:10:42,066
How to select the best sample from a data set

149
00:10:42,706 --> 00:10:44,126
when you have to go through them linearly.

150
00:10:44,766 --> 00:10:47,187
So the idea is, this kind of fictional scenario is,

151
00:10:47,747 --> 00:10:48,887
you're trying to hire a secretary.

152
00:10:49,107 --> 00:10:50,468
Secretaries are all different quality.

153
00:10:50,488 --> 00:10:51,728
Some of them are great, some of them are bad.

154
00:10:52,728 --> 00:10:54,688
And when you interview them,

155
00:10:54,889 --> 00:10:56,629
you can assess the quality of that person.

156
00:10:57,509 --> 00:10:59,229
But for whatever reason in this fictional scenario,

157
00:10:59,289 --> 00:11:02,250
once you say no and reject that applicant,

158
00:11:02,430 --> 00:11:04,450
they're gone forever and you can never call them back.

159
00:11:07,434 --> 00:11:11,819
And so the challenge is, how many people do you interview before you take the next best one?

160
00:11:12,280 --> 00:11:15,143
Right, if you interview two, three people, someone great comes along,

161
00:11:15,724 --> 00:11:17,647
and you're like, oh, they seem good, let's just hire them.

162
00:11:18,127 --> 00:11:22,232
How do you know that three people down the line, you wouldn't have someone much better?

163
00:11:23,514 --> 00:11:27,876
And so we were really worried about this with our brainstorming and conception process.

164
00:11:28,216 --> 00:11:30,477
We were brainstorming some ideas, some of them sounded cool,

165
00:11:31,938 --> 00:11:34,119
you know, maybe we'd even make a prototype and that would be cool,

166
00:11:34,159 --> 00:11:36,480
but how did we know that if we hadn't gone a couple more rounds,

167
00:11:36,820 --> 00:11:38,561
we wouldn't have come up with something much more compelling?

168
00:11:41,002 --> 00:11:45,624
So we had these four problems, and, you know, we looked at them and we said,

169
00:11:45,664 --> 00:11:47,825
okay, let's, you know, how are we going to address these?

170
00:11:47,845 --> 00:11:51,686
How are we going to change our process to try to mitigate this as best as we could?

171
00:11:52,868 --> 00:11:57,731
So what we decided to do, one, we wanted to rethink the typical brainstorming process,

172
00:11:57,751 --> 00:11:59,431
and I'll go through that in more detail in a second.

173
00:12:00,692 --> 00:12:03,813
Second, we wanted to make it completely democratic and fair.

174
00:12:04,593 --> 00:12:11,156
In order to use our tiny team, both as the idea generation and development,

175
00:12:11,176 --> 00:12:16,598
but also as our smallest and easiest validation of the ideas,

176
00:12:17,259 --> 00:12:19,280
we would have people vote on the best ideas,

177
00:12:19,920 --> 00:12:22,161
and make it a completely fair and democratic process.

178
00:12:23,500 --> 00:12:26,541
Third, we'd prototype as many things as possible.

179
00:12:27,082 --> 00:12:30,784
In order to validate that what sounded fun on paper

180
00:12:31,724 --> 00:12:33,786
actually was a compelling idea,

181
00:12:34,346 --> 00:12:37,628
we would rapidly prototype as many things as possible

182
00:12:38,308 --> 00:12:39,929
to validate their success.

183
00:12:40,590 --> 00:12:43,111
And fourth, once we had those prototypes,

184
00:12:43,231 --> 00:12:46,493
once we had that, no matter how compelling they were,

185
00:12:47,401 --> 00:12:52,264
We would put it aside, success or failure, and completely restart from scratch with a

186
00:12:52,284 --> 00:12:53,125
new batch of ideas.

187
00:12:53,685 --> 00:12:57,728
And we would do that for a period of time that we kind of figured out based on our schedule.

188
00:12:58,628 --> 00:13:02,891
And at the end of that, we'd look back over everything and say, OK, out of all this time,

189
00:13:02,931 --> 00:13:06,533
what were the ideas, what were the best ideas that we came up with during that period?

190
00:13:08,536 --> 00:13:11,877
So once we had those solutions, we split this into a plan.

191
00:13:12,017 --> 00:13:15,718
We had a two-week schedule where we would brainstorm,

192
00:13:15,778 --> 00:13:18,679
pitch, vote, plan, and then the second week we'd prototype.

193
00:13:19,679 --> 00:13:21,800
And then rinse, repeat, go right back to the beginning.

194
00:13:23,821 --> 00:13:25,421
And the first chunk of that is brainstorming.

195
00:13:26,001 --> 00:13:27,242
So for us, we had this challenge.

196
00:13:27,302 --> 00:13:30,503
Okay, how do we reinvent?

197
00:13:30,523 --> 00:13:32,403
How do we do a better job with brainstorming?

198
00:13:34,324 --> 00:13:37,345
The first problem we had was this wide-open mandate.

199
00:13:39,080 --> 00:13:40,702
You know, how the heck are we going to ask people to brainstorm?

200
00:13:40,722 --> 00:13:42,403
We're like, okay, group of people, go away.

201
00:13:42,924 --> 00:13:43,785
Just come up with anything.

202
00:13:44,045 --> 00:13:44,886
I don't know, like what are you into?

203
00:13:44,926 --> 00:13:47,169
Are you into RPGs, MMOs?

204
00:13:47,649 --> 00:13:49,471
You know, just throw some ideas out there,

205
00:13:49,511 --> 00:13:50,833
because our mandate could be anything.

206
00:13:51,614 --> 00:13:53,516
So, you know, we had to give some focus to that.

207
00:13:54,477 --> 00:13:58,080
We had to get some clarity as to where people should focus their brainstorming.

208
00:13:58,140 --> 00:13:59,521
What problem were they trying to solve?

209
00:14:00,321 --> 00:14:03,984
And so, you know, we worked on this idea of a guiding question.

210
00:14:04,445 --> 00:14:07,187
It had to be an open-ended question, we didn't want to force people into a corner,

211
00:14:08,007 --> 00:14:10,289
but we wanted this kind of open-ended guiding question

212
00:14:10,309 --> 00:14:13,592
that could help clarify and give them a direction to go in.

213
00:14:13,792 --> 00:14:15,133
So some examples of these questions.

214
00:14:16,274 --> 00:14:19,396
What game would you create where the primary mechanic is collaboration?

215
00:14:22,519 --> 00:14:27,262
What E for Everyone game would you create with 10,000 simultaneous AI or human characters?

216
00:14:29,464 --> 00:14:33,027
What exploration-based game could only be accomplished on a living room console with

217
00:14:33,087 --> 00:14:33,527
a peripheral?

218
00:14:34,187 --> 00:14:37,530
And there was a number of these different ideas and different questions that we put

219
00:14:37,570 --> 00:14:37,870
out there.

220
00:14:38,991 --> 00:14:44,715
One of my personal favorites that I didn't put up here was, what's a game that could

221
00:14:44,735 --> 00:14:46,937
evoke a sense of discovery and wonder?

222
00:14:47,437 --> 00:14:51,240
What would be a primary mechanic that could evoke a sense of discovery and wonder in players?

223
00:14:54,284 --> 00:14:59,970
So, once we had these questions, we had to set about brainstorming those.

224
00:15:00,671 --> 00:15:04,054
And the first thing that we did to combat this problem of the loudest person in the

225
00:15:04,094 --> 00:15:09,880
room was we scaled the brainstorming way down to the smallest it could be with one person.

226
00:15:11,133 --> 00:15:13,274
We'd start the first day of the week, this is Monday,

227
00:15:13,855 --> 00:15:15,516
we've got the question out, first thing,

228
00:15:16,537 --> 00:15:19,379
and everyone goes off alone to think about that question

229
00:15:19,939 --> 00:15:21,520
and to brainstorm on their own.

230
00:15:22,181 --> 00:15:24,142
And they could do a little bit of research, check things out,

231
00:15:24,523 --> 00:15:26,184
but they had the whole morning of the first day,

232
00:15:28,085 --> 00:15:30,987
and we tasked everyone with writing down 25

233
00:15:32,008 --> 00:15:36,291
compelling game ideas based on that question.

234
00:15:37,520 --> 00:15:39,321
And this doesn't sound too difficult, right?

235
00:15:39,401 --> 00:15:40,521
25 is not that big of a number.

236
00:15:42,162 --> 00:15:43,943
I assure you if you try to go through the exercise,

237
00:15:44,003 --> 00:15:45,764
it's much more challenging than you would think.

238
00:15:46,664 --> 00:15:49,206
You tend to get through 10, 15 ideas.

239
00:15:49,246 --> 00:15:50,426
You're like, yeah, this is easy.

240
00:15:50,446 --> 00:15:51,527
I am laughing.

241
00:15:52,227 --> 00:15:52,827
This is awesome.

242
00:15:53,848 --> 00:15:54,568
And then you get up to like 16, 17.

243
00:15:54,969 --> 00:15:57,210
You're like, OK, these are a bit of a stretch.

244
00:15:57,990 --> 00:15:59,831
And by the time you're at like 21, 22, 23, you hit 25,

245
00:15:59,971 --> 00:16:01,012
and you are like, that is it.

246
00:16:05,133 --> 00:16:10,156
This is the sum total of all possible human creativity about this subject.

247
00:16:10,216 --> 00:16:14,359
There are no other ideas imaginable that could answer this question.

248
00:16:14,579 --> 00:16:15,100
I've got them all.

249
00:16:16,220 --> 00:16:16,861
I am tapped out.

250
00:16:18,622 --> 00:16:20,844
And when people hit that point, we pair them up.

251
00:16:22,004 --> 00:16:26,507
And all of a sudden, you meet someone else from your team who's also done the same exercise,

252
00:16:26,768 --> 00:16:28,008
coming up with 25 ideas.

253
00:16:28,849 --> 00:16:30,350
And lo and behold, somehow...

254
00:16:31,380 --> 00:16:33,946
They've come up with a completely different set of 25 than you have.

255
00:16:34,507 --> 00:16:37,333
Oh, they saw this problem from a totally different perspective.

256
00:16:37,353 --> 00:16:38,797
They were coming at this from a different angle.

257
00:16:38,817 --> 00:16:41,062
I didn't even think of interpreting it like that.

258
00:16:41,940 --> 00:16:45,181
And so these two people would meet up, they'd share their ideas, they'd discuss their ideas,

259
00:16:45,821 --> 00:16:50,282
and the remarkable thing is that now both people are invigorated,

260
00:16:50,482 --> 00:16:54,083
they are suddenly seeing a different perspective that they never even thought of approaching this problem from.

261
00:16:54,603 --> 00:16:58,684
And together as a pair, they're tasked with coming up with an additional 25 ideas,

262
00:16:59,484 --> 00:17:01,284
riffing off inspiration from each other,

263
00:17:01,944 --> 00:17:05,845
you know, suddenly opening up entire new avenues of thought that neither of them considered,

264
00:17:05,865 --> 00:17:08,486
but, you know, once they saw the angle that each of them came from,

265
00:17:08,806 --> 00:17:09,966
it would open up this possibility.

266
00:17:11,303 --> 00:17:16,487
So by the end of the first day, each pair would have 75 ideas.

267
00:17:18,709 --> 00:17:20,471
Day two, we do it again.

268
00:17:21,111 --> 00:17:21,852
We take the pairs.

269
00:17:22,172 --> 00:17:22,753
We pair them up.

270
00:17:23,493 --> 00:17:24,614
So now we have groups of four.

271
00:17:25,375 --> 00:17:28,558
They share the 150 ideas that they came up

272
00:17:28,638 --> 00:17:29,799
with the previous day.

273
00:17:30,960 --> 00:17:32,041
And they start riffing.

274
00:17:32,061 --> 00:17:33,822
And as a group, now they're coming up with another 25.

275
00:17:36,287 --> 00:17:38,209
Afternoon, now we bring everyone in.

276
00:17:39,129 --> 00:17:41,111
And we literally have hundreds of ideas.

277
00:17:41,151 --> 00:17:44,653
When any individual couldn't possibly think

278
00:17:44,693 --> 00:17:47,575
of more than 25, now the whole team is empowered

279
00:17:47,616 --> 00:17:49,577
with a set of hundreds of ideas

280
00:17:49,937 --> 00:17:51,258
answering this open-ended question

281
00:17:51,779 --> 00:17:52,719
from which they can draw from.

282
00:17:55,221 --> 00:17:58,203
And then the last step is to scale all the way back down.

283
00:18:00,405 --> 00:18:03,327
Right back down to single, solo work.

284
00:18:04,321 --> 00:18:08,723
Where each individual had two full days to take those hundreds of ideas,

285
00:18:09,444 --> 00:18:12,185
to take all of that huge possibility space,

286
00:18:12,886 --> 00:18:15,147
and condense that down into three pitches.

287
00:18:16,488 --> 00:18:18,289
Three slides each, five minutes each,

288
00:18:19,369 --> 00:18:22,731
that were, you know, fleshing some of those ideas out

289
00:18:22,871 --> 00:18:27,113
into something that they thought was a compelling and cohesive game pitch.

290
00:18:28,267 --> 00:18:30,128
So they distill all of that info down.

291
00:18:31,169 --> 00:18:33,051
And at the end of day Thursday, we'd get everyone

292
00:18:33,091 --> 00:18:34,533
together in a room.

293
00:18:35,474 --> 00:18:36,214
And it was very fun.

294
00:18:36,234 --> 00:18:37,295
We had kind of a pitch day.

295
00:18:37,335 --> 00:18:41,660
And everyone had their five minutes to go up, or five

296
00:18:41,680 --> 00:18:45,603
minutes per, to go up and present their pitches, present

297
00:18:45,623 --> 00:18:46,084
their ideas.

298
00:18:47,045 --> 00:18:49,467
And it was amazing seeing even the ideas that you had seen in

299
00:18:49,667 --> 00:18:51,049
very early stages.

300
00:18:53,085 --> 00:18:57,628
At a brainstorming level, you know, once people had really put thought in and attached images

301
00:18:57,708 --> 00:19:04,353
and kind of put some work in to put that into a cohesive and fleshed out pitch, it was absolutely

302
00:19:04,393 --> 00:19:07,715
incredible seeing these just dozens and dozens of

303
00:19:08,516 --> 00:19:13,201
Amazing game pitches come together and I still think there are a treasure trove, you know,

304
00:19:13,221 --> 00:19:17,666
going back through our old files of so many games that I would love to make at some point in the

305
00:19:17,706 --> 00:19:23,993
future. Incredibly creative and diverse ideas that, you know, we would never have gotten

306
00:19:24,033 --> 00:19:25,074
through a traditional process.

307
00:19:26,755 --> 00:19:28,036
Once we had these pitches, everyone voted.

308
00:19:29,356 --> 00:19:30,157
We did this very simply.

309
00:19:30,197 --> 00:19:34,519
We just gave everyone three little circle sticky things.

310
00:19:35,199 --> 00:19:36,380
And everyone went up and voted.

311
00:19:36,840 --> 00:19:39,561
As people were pitching, we'd write them down on the board.

312
00:19:40,582 --> 00:19:43,103
And people could go up and vote on the ones that they wanted.

313
00:19:44,103 --> 00:19:52,389
Now one improvement to this, this process is actually being taken and replicated over at Magic Leap in New Zealand,

314
00:19:53,029 --> 00:19:57,252
where James Everett, who was the original designer, has gone to, the lead designer.

315
00:19:57,272 --> 00:19:57,333
And...

316
00:19:59,774 --> 00:20:03,196
One of the improvements that they made, one of the iterations that they made on this process

317
00:20:03,896 --> 00:20:11,660
was to make the votes silent because you know you get some pattern of people looking at what

318
00:20:11,680 --> 00:20:17,323
other people are voting on and and steering that. We didn't do that when we did it originally and

319
00:20:17,923 --> 00:20:20,064
I think it worked well but you know it may have just been the way that our

320
00:20:20,904 --> 00:20:27,367
that our group was structured and that we were going up. So everyone would vote and

321
00:20:29,374 --> 00:20:33,276
After we'd voted, we'd have three top voted pitches.

322
00:20:33,636 --> 00:20:35,537
Now, many times these three top voted pitches

323
00:20:36,657 --> 00:20:38,418
actually came from four or five pitches.

324
00:20:38,658 --> 00:20:41,019
It's really strange the way that kind of zeitgeist works.

325
00:20:41,579 --> 00:20:45,601
People have the same set of raw ideas that they're drawing from

326
00:20:45,661 --> 00:20:47,582
and sometimes you get pitches that, you know,

327
00:20:47,602 --> 00:20:48,902
were going in a similar direction.

328
00:20:49,543 --> 00:20:51,603
So rather than say like, oh, this one got slightly more votes,

329
00:20:51,624 --> 00:20:53,664
we'd say those two pitches were pretty much along the same lines.

330
00:20:53,704 --> 00:20:54,405
Let's merge them.

331
00:20:55,225 --> 00:20:57,206
You know, let's combine the cool elements of both

332
00:20:57,246 --> 00:20:58,506
and turn that into one thing.

333
00:20:59,067 --> 00:21:03,370
But essentially we'd boil it down to three winning pitches each time.

334
00:21:04,591 --> 00:21:07,473
And from there, everyone would submit their preferences of like,

335
00:21:07,513 --> 00:21:09,054
hey, I'd love to work on prototyping.

336
00:21:10,098 --> 00:21:12,039
This pitch or that pitch in order.

337
00:21:12,739 --> 00:21:14,500
And we'd look and it was a very small team,

338
00:21:14,600 --> 00:21:17,202
so we had to just make some decisions and break it up.

339
00:21:18,062 --> 00:21:22,225
And each person would end up joining a small group

340
00:21:22,305 --> 00:21:26,027
of two, three people, as we grew maybe three, four,

341
00:21:26,107 --> 00:21:28,909
five people to work on a prototype.

342
00:21:29,169 --> 00:21:32,791
And we made three prototypes in a week, every two weeks.

343
00:21:34,691 --> 00:21:41,414
So we'd have one day, the Friday of that week, to break into those groups, sit down, start

344
00:21:41,454 --> 00:21:49,117
talking, start talking about how the heck in a week can we possibly prototype.

345
00:21:49,137 --> 00:21:50,358
These were big game ideas.

346
00:21:50,378 --> 00:21:50,818
These were like...

347
00:21:51,738 --> 00:21:56,619
Not a mini-game, these were pitches for something that could be a AAA game.

348
00:21:57,200 --> 00:22:02,061
And so, you know, in a week, how do you get down, how do you boil down to the essence of that idea?

349
00:22:02,461 --> 00:22:05,082
And how do you validate that in the most efficient manner possible?

350
00:22:06,022 --> 00:22:07,483
And there is never any extra time.

351
00:22:07,863 --> 00:22:09,344
Literally, there is only a week, that's it.

352
00:22:09,564 --> 00:22:10,204
That's what you have to do.

353
00:22:11,885 --> 00:22:18,769
So people would kind of come up with a plan, and then in the afternoon we'd run those plans by the other groups, get some feedback, get some validation.

354
00:22:19,110 --> 00:22:27,215
Often you'd have suggestions for, hey, maybe you could use this technology, maybe there's this tool you could use, did you know that this was out there, that would be helpful.

355
00:22:28,396 --> 00:22:32,339
And then we had a week to validate by any means necessary.

356
00:22:34,412 --> 00:22:36,633
We used different engines.

357
00:22:37,353 --> 00:22:39,114
We used different tech that was available.

358
00:22:39,654 --> 00:22:43,676
We made paper prototypes or acted things out

359
00:22:43,776 --> 00:22:46,858
or did anything we possibly could to prove this out.

360
00:22:47,778 --> 00:22:52,461
And again, this was a wonderful process.

361
00:22:53,061 --> 00:22:54,102
It was a mad dash.

362
00:22:54,442 --> 00:22:55,522
It was very, uh...

363
00:22:56,443 --> 00:23:02,429
Intense for a week making all of these games and this resulted in all sorts of wild and wacky

364
00:23:02,449 --> 00:23:06,653
prototypes across all sorts of different technologies and genres and things and

365
00:23:08,354 --> 00:23:09,155
lots of crazy stuff

366
00:23:10,776 --> 00:23:17,883
AR and and mobile things and whatever. I don't even know what was going on here. This is

367
00:23:19,370 --> 00:23:20,591
I'm sure it was a ton of fun.

368
00:23:21,533 --> 00:23:26,679
And these photos were from something, I mostly put them in just to embarrass these people

369
00:23:26,719 --> 00:23:28,401
that they were in my GDC presentation.

370
00:23:31,645 --> 00:23:34,068
Yeah, these games were amazing, I'm sure.

371
00:23:35,522 --> 00:23:37,644
Anyways, we came up with all sorts of crazy prototypes.

372
00:23:38,505 --> 00:23:43,190
One of those prototypes was actually really cool, and I'll show you a quick video of it.

373
00:23:45,272 --> 00:23:49,176
It was a game where you could, it was used to connect and you could kind of make these

374
00:23:49,256 --> 00:23:51,558
silhouette paintings with your body.

375
00:23:52,679 --> 00:23:55,480
and capture them, and it was kind of a Pictionary kind of thing, right, people would guess.

