00:23:56,021 --> 00:23:58,642
And, you know, this was something that we didn't think,

377
00:23:58,702 --> 00:24:01,383
okay, maybe this isn't something we're going to turn into a big AAA game.

378
00:24:02,143 --> 00:24:04,004
But we actually had a chance to show it to the world.

379
00:24:04,504 --> 00:24:08,306
There's an all-night festival called Nuit Blanche in Toronto.

380
00:24:08,666 --> 00:24:12,467
And so we went and projected it up on the side of a seven-story building

381
00:24:12,508 --> 00:24:14,588
and had everyone come out and play it. It was super cool.

382
00:24:17,080 --> 00:24:22,463
After we did all this prototyping, we'd all get together, big group, play all these games,

383
00:24:23,323 --> 00:24:28,526
have a ton of fun, and give this really open and honest feedback on what worked, what didn't.

384
00:24:31,220 --> 00:24:36,145
The power of this feeling of fairness, because it was this democratic process, you know,

385
00:24:36,205 --> 00:24:42,351
everyone had been voting, there wasn't one idea selected because, you know, the lead

386
00:24:42,431 --> 00:24:45,174
said this is the one we're going to go, this is the direction I want to go in.

387
00:24:45,654 --> 00:24:50,479
Everyone felt like it was a fair playing field where each of them had contributed to that.

388
00:24:50,959 --> 00:24:54,903
And that had an incredible effect on people's willingness to step up.

389
00:24:56,425 --> 00:25:01,850
You know, give their honest thoughts on what was working, what they were excited about, what fell through.

390
00:25:02,211 --> 00:25:05,714
And I think this is something that you actually see a lot in game jam culture as well.

391
00:25:06,535 --> 00:25:11,700
You know, this incredibly open and transparent and honest feedback and assessment.

392
00:25:11,720 --> 00:25:22,330
I think it's a really positive part of that community that oftentimes we miss out and we get a little bit wrapped up in politics and, you know, power politics in larger development.

393
00:25:24,835 --> 00:25:29,938
After all that, we went for a while, we had dozens of prototypes,

394
00:25:30,659 --> 00:25:32,460
and we reached that point where we were like,

395
00:25:32,480 --> 00:25:34,141
okay, we really need to decide what we're going to do.

396
00:25:34,861 --> 00:25:36,822
And so we took a step back and we looked through.

397
00:25:38,423 --> 00:25:41,865
Keeping in mind that secretary problem, we had really given it a good run.

398
00:25:41,905 --> 00:25:43,846
We had a bunch of stuff that we could select from.

399
00:25:44,847 --> 00:25:48,889
And we looked back, and out of everything, one prototype really stood out.

