00:29:30,648 --> 00:29:32,629
but you could just see this magic

465
00:29:33,909 --> 00:29:37,130
that it was something that they absolutely fell in love with.

466
00:29:38,310 --> 00:29:40,231
And so we knew we were onto something special,

467
00:29:40,451 --> 00:29:41,271
and we took this game.

468
00:29:42,836 --> 00:29:46,157
And we brought it to Ubisoft's HQ in Paris

469
00:29:46,177 --> 00:29:46,977
and we presented it.

470
00:29:48,618 --> 00:29:49,879
And it went super well.

471
00:29:50,019 --> 00:29:52,019
They were really happy, the pitch went well,

472
00:29:52,059 --> 00:29:52,780
they were excited.

473
00:29:52,800 --> 00:29:55,881
And we showed a little bit of all these crazy

474
00:29:56,501 --> 00:29:57,701
prototypes and things we'd built.

475
00:30:01,003 --> 00:30:03,864
We got a green light, and so that moves us

476
00:30:03,904 --> 00:30:05,184
into the next phase of our story,

477
00:30:05,204 --> 00:30:06,865
which is pre-production.

478
00:30:08,565 --> 00:30:10,766
So coming back from our successful pitch,

479
00:30:11,126 --> 00:30:11,906
we were feeling great.

480
00:30:12,902 --> 00:30:15,503
We started to grow the team, expand the team, bring people on.

481
00:30:17,143 --> 00:30:20,424
And we were feeling amazing, on top of the world.

482
00:30:20,484 --> 00:30:22,665
We were like, this is it, we're kicking ass.

483
00:30:22,905 --> 00:30:24,805
We threw out all of the old process.

484
00:30:24,845 --> 00:30:27,466
We did this crazy new experiment.

485
00:30:27,826 --> 00:30:28,826
It was super successful.

486
00:30:29,947 --> 00:30:33,448
So we felt vindicated for trying to do things differently.

487
00:30:34,508 --> 00:30:38,109
And we were incredibly overambitious, super audacious.

488
00:30:38,129 --> 00:30:39,869
We were like, we're gonna do everything at this point,

489
00:30:40,429 --> 00:30:41,250
just, you know.

490
00:30:42,616 --> 00:30:44,437
Who thought we could do anything to do with hardware?

491
00:30:45,298 --> 00:30:48,780
This'll be awesome, just throw more crazy stuff on the pile.

492
00:30:50,381 --> 00:30:53,043
And, you know, but we still knew that we were a new team,

493
00:30:53,063 --> 00:30:55,305
we were a small team, and we needed to prove ourselves.

494
00:30:56,405 --> 00:30:58,267
So we set about making a vertical slice.

495
00:30:58,447 --> 00:31:00,488
You know, we fully recognized that the little demo

496
00:31:00,528 --> 00:31:02,730
that we showed to kids, you know,

497
00:31:02,750 --> 00:31:04,051
that was never something that could have shipped.

498
00:31:04,291 --> 00:31:06,913
It was, you know, a hacky kind of little demo

499
00:31:06,953 --> 00:31:07,673
that made something work.

500
00:31:08,731 --> 00:31:10,858
So we set out to prove that we could do this for real.

501
00:31:11,078 --> 00:31:15,592
We could make a game and make a toy that looked and felt like something that could go to market.

502
00:31:17,219 --> 00:31:21,442
And so, you know, filled with energy, filled with enthusiasm, we charged into this,

503
00:31:22,663 --> 00:31:24,704
and it started going pretty well.

504
00:31:25,524 --> 00:31:27,466
This is our next iteration.

505
00:31:27,746 --> 00:31:28,666
Those are the connectors.

506
00:31:28,727 --> 00:31:31,008
So we got rid of those horrible micro USB connectors,

507
00:31:31,628 --> 00:31:34,570
and we made these really neat connectors that we'd click together and they'd work,

508
00:31:35,271 --> 00:31:38,053
and, you know, have this really instantaneous connection to the game.

509
00:31:39,233 --> 00:31:41,655
And, you know, we made our first real toys.

510
00:31:43,376 --> 00:31:44,877
These are some of the early...

511
00:31:47,278 --> 00:31:51,163
You know, the first version of real-looking toys that we made.

512
00:31:51,203 --> 00:31:53,907
We started to bring on some people from the toy industry that knew what they were doing.

513
00:31:54,808 --> 00:31:58,874
We started working with model shops and people that could, you know, really make...

514
00:31:59,977 --> 00:32:01,819
Proper professional toy prototypes.

515
00:32:03,140 --> 00:32:04,741
And we made these toys, they looked really cool.

516
00:32:05,382 --> 00:32:07,784
You know, they had problems, there's certainly usability things.

517
00:32:08,445 --> 00:32:13,069
I have gained an immense amount of respect for toy designers and toy industry and everything that they do.

518
00:32:13,749 --> 00:32:21,136
And so, you know, you'd move these toys and the wings, you know, would kind of fall off because these connectors were great, but didn't really have anything that would latch or connect.

519
00:32:22,437 --> 00:32:23,938
And we built a demo.

520
00:32:25,809 --> 00:32:27,851
This was our first vertical slice demo.

521
00:32:28,572 --> 00:32:30,693
And, you know, it was really coming together.

522
00:32:30,733 --> 00:32:32,815
It was something that was a big step forward

523
00:32:33,776 --> 00:32:36,438
from, you know, the little prototypes that we had made.

524
00:32:36,458 --> 00:32:37,600
It was pretty neat.

525
00:32:37,620 --> 00:32:38,640
You'd start out in space,

526
00:32:39,821 --> 00:32:42,324
kind of take off from this mothership,

527
00:32:43,965 --> 00:32:44,626
and, uh...

528
00:32:45,702 --> 00:32:46,803
Eventually launch.

529
00:32:47,844 --> 00:32:49,446
And then you'd arrive out in space,

530
00:32:49,486 --> 00:32:51,488
and there was kind of these different levels

531
00:32:51,528 --> 00:32:53,951
that you could select down on the planet's surface,

532
00:32:54,191 --> 00:32:55,192
these different linear levels.

533
00:32:55,232 --> 00:32:56,453
And you could look at one of these gates

534
00:32:56,513 --> 00:32:57,815
and say, oh, I want to do that.

535
00:32:58,375 --> 00:33:00,698
And then you transition down to the surface.

536
00:33:00,718 --> 00:33:01,759
There was a loading sequence.

537
00:33:02,519 --> 00:33:04,602
And you'd engage on whatever mission it was.

538
00:33:04,662 --> 00:33:06,904
So in this example, it was a race.

539
00:33:07,625 --> 00:33:09,366
And you'd go and start engaging that.

540
00:33:09,688 --> 00:33:13,232
It was pretty cool, and everything you do on the toy would be instantly recreated,

541
00:33:13,272 --> 00:33:18,557
and you could add all these weapons or boosters or things that could change the gameplay.

542
00:33:20,219 --> 00:33:24,383
And so we made this demo, we're feeling great, we're like on top of the world, kicking ass.

543
00:33:25,224 --> 00:33:28,348
We bring it back and we're like, okay, here's where we're at, this is our vertical slice, it's awesome.

544
00:33:29,482 --> 00:33:32,763
And that's when we realized, OK, this is starting to get real.

545
00:33:33,183 --> 00:33:34,484
We're playing in a bit of a different league.

546
00:33:34,504 --> 00:33:36,864
There's real money on the table.

547
00:33:36,964 --> 00:33:38,245
We're building a bigger team here.

548
00:33:39,665 --> 00:33:41,926
The stakes are a lot higher, and the expectations

549
00:33:41,946 --> 00:33:42,546
are a lot higher.

550
00:33:43,466 --> 00:33:45,647
It's no longer good enough just to have something

551
00:33:45,667 --> 00:33:47,287
that's a cool idea, a compelling demo.

552
00:33:48,027 --> 00:33:50,888
And we start hearing all of this feedback of, really?

553
00:33:51,048 --> 00:33:53,229
You guys making a custom controller?

554
00:33:53,969 --> 00:33:56,330
Do you know how long Microsoft and Sony and Nintendo

555
00:33:56,570 --> 00:33:57,750
spend on making a controller?

556
00:33:59,064 --> 00:33:59,724
A pretty big endeavor.

557
00:34:00,765 --> 00:34:02,726
And you know, the engine that you're working with,

558
00:34:02,806 --> 00:34:04,647
I'm not sure you're going to ship with that.

559
00:34:04,707 --> 00:34:07,728
And the game structure, and player engagement,

560
00:34:07,808 --> 00:34:11,450
and play time, and world logic, and all these things

561
00:34:11,470 --> 00:34:13,431
that you need to figure out for building a new IP.

562
00:34:14,312 --> 00:34:17,813
You know, really real, valid things

563
00:34:17,853 --> 00:34:22,316
that we were just kind of rushing through with vim

564
00:34:22,336 --> 00:34:22,636
and vigor.

565
00:34:24,286 --> 00:34:26,248
But in addition to all of these external things,

566
00:34:27,088 --> 00:34:29,611
we started having these voices cropping up within our team,

567
00:34:31,372 --> 00:34:35,115
saying, hey guys, I think maybe we should take a step back

568
00:34:35,195 --> 00:34:37,757
and kind of plan this out properly

569
00:34:38,138 --> 00:34:39,819
and figure out what our scope is.

570
00:34:42,001 --> 00:34:45,304
This process is cool, but it's a bit chaotic.

571
00:34:45,344 --> 00:34:47,386
This is a bit seat of our pants, right?

572
00:34:47,786 --> 00:34:49,988
We should really document this, do all of this.

573
00:34:50,728 --> 00:34:52,730
And at this point, we had two paths ahead of us.

574
00:34:53,659 --> 00:34:54,299
We had a big choice.

575
00:34:56,700 --> 00:35:00,561
We could thoroughly document, you know, scope it out,

576
00:35:00,801 --> 00:35:02,282
rigorous process, analyze requests.

577
00:35:02,302 --> 00:35:04,643
This is how, you know, Ubisoft has proven

578
00:35:05,343 --> 00:35:06,283
these processes out.

579
00:35:06,503 --> 00:35:07,543
This is how we make games.

580
00:35:08,684 --> 00:35:10,264
You know, people have figured this out.

581
00:35:10,404 --> 00:35:13,265
We've got Jira and Confluence,

582
00:35:13,325 --> 00:35:15,566
and yeah, we can like really button this down.

583
00:35:16,606 --> 00:35:19,547
You have to remember that this group of people

584
00:35:19,907 --> 00:35:20,528
making this thing,

585
00:35:21,660 --> 00:35:25,802
Kind of all pulled together specifically to rebel against this kind of process, right?

586
00:35:26,162 --> 00:35:28,203
It was kind of a group of people that were specifically like,

587
00:35:28,443 --> 00:35:33,966
ah, you know, to us this was the boring and slow, but you know, maybe sensible,

588
00:35:34,406 --> 00:35:38,988
but boring and slow path that, you know, that we wanted to go away from.

589
00:35:39,649 --> 00:35:41,730
And so to us, we saw another choice.

590
00:35:43,551 --> 00:35:44,191
More innovation.

591
00:35:45,952 --> 00:35:50,274
No matter what challenge came up, we could always solve it with more innovation.

592
00:35:53,048 --> 00:35:57,712
And there's two guys that I wished I had paid more attention to, in retrospect.

593
00:35:58,793 --> 00:36:00,955
Their names are Abraham Maslow and Vilfredo Pareto.

594
00:36:00,975 --> 00:36:04,378
Does anyone know what Maslow is, what I'm referring to in this case?

595
00:36:07,620 --> 00:36:08,241
Hierarchy of Needs.

596
00:36:09,742 --> 00:36:13,185
No, not the Hierarchy of Needs. He is very famous for the Hierarchy of Needs.

597
00:36:14,046 --> 00:36:17,088
But not that, thank you for playing into my GDC presentation thing.

598
00:36:17,806 --> 00:36:22,669
Specifically, I am talking about Maslow's hammer,

599
00:36:23,729 --> 00:36:25,330
or the expression that when you have a hammer,

600
00:36:26,411 --> 00:36:27,372
everything looks like a nail.

601
00:36:29,313 --> 00:36:33,215
And Vilfredo Pareto is famous for the Pareto Principle,

602
00:36:33,416 --> 00:36:34,456
or the 80-20 rule.

603
00:36:35,657 --> 00:36:38,019
The principle that 20% of the effort

604
00:36:38,119 --> 00:36:39,620
will yield 80% of the results,

605
00:36:39,720 --> 00:36:42,441
and that final 20% of the results that you need

606
00:36:43,042 --> 00:36:44,002
actually comes from 80% of the effort.

607
00:36:47,056 --> 00:36:47,916
Because we had a hammer.

608
00:36:49,877 --> 00:36:51,977
And that hammer was more innovation.

609
00:36:52,757 --> 00:36:54,518
The whole process that we had created

610
00:36:55,298 --> 00:36:57,379
was effectively an innovation machine.

611
00:36:58,399 --> 00:37:00,540
And so no matter what feedback came up,

612
00:37:00,800 --> 00:37:02,040
no matter what challenge came up,

613
00:37:02,860 --> 00:37:05,061
we could innovate our way out of that problem.

614
00:37:05,581 --> 00:37:09,162
So too expensive and difficult to create a custom game

615
00:37:09,182 --> 00:37:09,622
controller.

616
00:37:10,442 --> 00:37:15,187
No problem. We'll make a controller mount that interfaces directly with the extension port

617
00:37:15,848 --> 00:37:21,593
of all of the first-party controllers, allowing you to communicate instantly through their

618
00:37:22,614 --> 00:37:25,897
hardware and leveraging all of that work in a way that no one's done before.

619
00:37:26,988 --> 00:37:31,533
More powerful tech? No problem. We'll take Ubisoft's latest and greatest engine, Snowdrop,

620
00:37:31,993 --> 00:37:39,560
and port everything over and leverage that work with an engine that is amazingly powerful,

621
00:37:39,921 --> 00:37:45,586
but at the time hadn't really been fully proven out and was still being used on the Division.

622
00:37:47,287 --> 00:37:49,369
More freedom and autonomy? No problem.

623
00:37:49,978 --> 00:37:54,120
We'll create tech to allow you to seamlessly travel from space to planets, planets to space,

624
00:37:54,180 --> 00:37:58,682
circumnavigate around worlds in a completely open and seamless manner.

625
00:38:03,404 --> 00:38:05,966
More meaningful choices? No problem.

626
00:38:06,526 --> 00:38:10,628
We'll simulate every single AI on every single planet simultaneously,

627
00:38:12,729 --> 00:38:15,810
allowing the players to have real impact on the planets.

628
00:38:17,369 --> 00:38:22,496
and allowing the enemy to fight back so that no two players will have the same story

629
00:38:22,716 --> 00:38:24,338
and everyone's game will go in a different direction.

630
00:38:28,662 --> 00:38:29,784
And, you know, we didn't stop there.

631
00:38:30,284 --> 00:38:33,908
No matter what came up, there was something new.

632
00:38:34,168 --> 00:38:38,152
We had crazy three-dimensional elemental propagation throughout the game.

633
00:38:38,252 --> 00:38:43,898
We had second screen experiences and planet creation at some point, ill advise.

634
00:38:45,720 --> 00:38:47,843
We wanted to build laser tag into the toy.

635
00:38:47,983 --> 00:38:49,805
I still kind of miss this idea, it would have been really cool.

636
00:38:53,658 --> 00:38:58,322
But we were really going out there, and we made all of this stuff, and we took a step

637
00:38:58,362 --> 00:39:00,303
back, and we were like, OK, where are we at?

638
00:39:01,865 --> 00:39:02,205
It worked.

639
00:39:02,565 --> 00:39:03,986
These were cool prototypes.

640
00:39:04,006 --> 00:39:05,327
They were amazing ideas.

641
00:39:06,268 --> 00:39:06,808
And they worked.

642
00:39:07,729 --> 00:39:12,372
We had this team that could make these crazy innovations functional and prove them out

643
00:39:12,452 --> 00:39:13,313
quickly and...

644
00:39:15,475 --> 00:39:16,455
Except for the other 80% of the work.

645
00:39:18,265 --> 00:39:20,107
that it would have taken to actually make those features.

646
00:39:20,708 --> 00:39:23,591
We had quickly gotten them to these 80% states of like,

647
00:39:23,792 --> 00:39:25,333
yeah, yeah, yeah, that's cool, that works.

648
00:39:25,914 --> 00:39:29,218
And when we started to take a step back and look at it,

649
00:39:30,379 --> 00:39:33,583
we were like, oh no, we made a huge mistake.

650
00:39:36,449 --> 00:39:40,270
And I'm not quite sure how all of these separate pieces were supposed to fit together.

651
00:39:40,690 --> 00:39:47,112
You know, individually they were all really neat innovations, but they weren't adding up to create a sum that was greater than the...

652
00:39:47,612 --> 00:39:49,073
a whole that was greater than the sum of its parts.

653
00:39:52,454 --> 00:39:57,055
And so, you know, we started to realize, okay, you know, this process that was amazing for conception,

654
00:39:57,795 --> 00:40:02,777
that was incredibly effective during the conception phase, I don't know if this is scaling in the way that we hoped it would.

655
00:40:07,185 --> 00:40:12,570
And while there were some of these features that were really groundbreaking and revolutionary

656
00:40:12,991 --> 00:40:18,957
and are still huge components of the game today, you know, this controller mount right

657
00:40:18,977 --> 00:40:23,321
at your fingertips instantly swapping out and the seamless travel and this incredible

658
00:40:23,401 --> 00:40:24,002
living world.

659
00:40:25,463 --> 00:40:30,345
So many more of the features ended up having to be cut and cast aside,

660
00:40:30,946 --> 00:40:36,729
and we wasted a lot of time and effort trying to innovate our way out of every problem,

661
00:40:37,169 --> 00:40:39,450
which we could have solved in a much better manner.

662
00:40:42,019 --> 00:40:45,422
And for me, this was really a moment, stepping back,

663
00:40:45,843 --> 00:40:48,765
and it was kind of this shattering of the reality distortion field.

664
00:40:49,646 --> 00:40:51,508
Engineers at Apple used to speak about

665
00:40:52,669 --> 00:40:54,610
something they called the reality distortion field,

666
00:40:55,031 --> 00:40:57,393
where the charisma of Steve Jobs

667
00:40:58,134 --> 00:41:04,002
I could convince people that the impossible was possible and that no matter what problem

668
00:41:04,042 --> 00:41:09,931
they faced, even when you couldn't push the silicon to do that, he could will it to happen

669
00:41:09,971 --> 00:41:12,535
and they would pull a group of people together and make it so.

670
00:41:13,596 --> 00:41:17,338
And, you know, honestly in the early phases of this project we felt like that.

671
00:41:17,418 --> 00:41:21,939
We felt like, okay, you know, no matter what happens, we've got this process, it's working.

672
00:41:22,400 --> 00:41:26,141
We will just will it to make it so, make it happen.

673
00:41:26,861 --> 00:41:30,103
And, you know, it was when we stood back and looked at this and said,

674
00:41:31,063 --> 00:41:34,624
okay, we're never going to ship this. It's not going to come together.

675
00:41:35,885 --> 00:41:39,586
You know, for me this was really this kind of low point of reflection.

676
00:41:40,987 --> 00:41:41,287
And that

677
00:41:42,358 --> 00:41:43,839
Brought us right into the beginning of production.

678
00:41:45,660 --> 00:41:49,463
With this question, how in the hell are we gonna ship this?

679
00:41:50,844 --> 00:41:51,785
How are we gonna make this,

680
00:41:52,606 --> 00:41:54,747
how are we gonna fix this process?

681
00:41:54,767 --> 00:41:57,049
We had all of these incredibly powerful

682
00:41:57,129 --> 00:41:58,650
and compelling parts.

683
00:41:59,291 --> 00:42:01,452
How are we gonna pull them together into a whole?

684
00:42:06,316 --> 00:42:06,896
A little voice.

685
00:42:09,598 --> 00:42:11,180
We can solve it with more innovation.

686
00:42:13,270 --> 00:42:15,470
We kind of realized, you know, maybe, maybe not.

687
00:42:16,491 --> 00:42:19,612
Maybe that was, in fact, part of the problem

688
00:42:19,792 --> 00:42:22,253
that had gotten us into this situation.

689
00:42:23,553 --> 00:42:25,634
In Ed Catmull's excellent book, Creativity Inc.,

690
00:42:26,354 --> 00:42:28,595
he talks about the importance of balance

691
00:42:29,135 --> 00:42:30,516
and the importance of conflict

692
00:42:30,876 --> 00:42:33,217
between all of the departments in a creative enterprise

693
00:42:33,777 --> 00:42:35,078
to maintain that balance.

694
00:42:35,998 --> 00:42:37,398
And when we took a step back and looked,

695
00:42:37,579 --> 00:42:42,120
we realized that our development was horribly unbalanced.

696
00:42:43,352 --> 00:42:50,759
And I want to clarify that this was not specific disciplines fighting against each other.

697
00:42:50,939 --> 00:42:57,024
This was not game designers wanting innovation and programmers saying no.

698
00:42:58,211 --> 00:43:03,793
You know, this was really guiding philosophies, and we had game designers pushing for, you

699
00:43:03,813 --> 00:43:08,835
know, more scope control and bringing things down to a more elegant solution.

700
00:43:09,115 --> 00:43:10,956
We had programmers pushing for more innovation.

701
00:43:11,937 --> 00:43:15,858
You know, these were these kind of competing philosophies, but what we realized was that

702
00:43:15,898 --> 00:43:20,560
the philosophy of innovation as solution was massively...

703
00:43:22,140 --> 00:43:23,781
Unbalanced and overweighted.

704
00:43:24,441 --> 00:43:28,102
And we had to take a step back and some of those voices that had been there within our team earlier,

705
00:43:29,502 --> 00:43:34,963
we had to put things in place to empower those voices and listen to those voices.

706
00:43:35,863 --> 00:43:40,324
You know, people in tech saying, OK, hey, it's great that we have these wonderful innovations,

707
00:43:40,704 --> 00:43:44,625
but we need to balance that out with safer solutions, with proven solutions,

708
00:43:44,665 --> 00:43:47,585
in order to protect the innovations and make them really sing.

709
00:43:48,506 --> 00:43:50,046
People in production saying, hey, we can help.

710
00:43:50,786 --> 00:43:55,150
make this scope more manageable, we can help address the timeline and adjust the timeline

711
00:43:55,190 --> 00:43:57,371
to make this a realistic endeavor.

712
00:43:58,172 --> 00:44:02,315
In business, saying, you know, we can help validate this offer, we can help validate

713
00:44:02,355 --> 00:44:07,820
which parts of this are really resonating, really pinpoint the audience and their expectations.

714
00:44:09,141 --> 00:44:12,804
Every GDC talk has to have some sort of cheesy analogy, so this is mine.

715
00:44:14,045 --> 00:44:15,086
I think of this as...

716
00:44:17,159 --> 00:44:23,283
trying to protect a spark, protect a flame, and grow it into a fire.

717
00:44:24,965 --> 00:44:30,109
And early on, too much process and too much innovation and too much structure can snuff

718
00:44:30,149 --> 00:44:32,090
that out, can, you know, really...

719
00:44:34,269 --> 00:44:38,591
squander and kill ideas way too early.

720
00:44:39,431 --> 00:44:41,692
And again, in Creativity Inc.,

721
00:44:41,772 --> 00:44:45,114
he talks about protecting ugly babies.

722
00:44:45,194 --> 00:44:47,235
That often these early prototypes

723
00:44:47,255 --> 00:44:49,075
that you're making with a couple people in a couple days,

724
00:44:49,716 --> 00:44:51,056
they're rough, they're rough around the edges.

725
00:44:51,096 --> 00:44:52,057
And if people looked at them,

726
00:44:52,737 --> 00:44:55,698
they'd be easy to dissect and they'd be easy to pick apart.

727
00:44:56,119 --> 00:44:58,220
And you need to give that time and space

728
00:44:58,280 --> 00:45:00,661
and freedom to survive.

729
00:45:01,972 --> 00:45:07,280
But what we realized is as you grow, without the structure,

730
00:45:07,680 --> 00:45:10,545
without the protection of that structure starting to come on board,

731
00:45:12,167 --> 00:45:15,792
you're actually doing an immense disservice to these sparks.

732
00:45:16,720 --> 00:45:19,922
New flames will spark up and consume all the oxygen.

733
00:45:20,022 --> 00:45:24,704
Winds of change will come as things change in the industry

734
00:45:24,764 --> 00:45:26,225
or things change with people's behavior

735
00:45:26,866 --> 00:45:30,128
and start to snuff out things that were promising.

736
00:45:30,408 --> 00:45:32,029
And you have to start putting these walls,

737
00:45:32,069 --> 00:45:33,449
starting to put this structure in place,

738
00:45:33,910 --> 00:45:37,912
bit by bit, leading up to protect the innovations that you have.

739
00:45:39,573 --> 00:45:41,934
And that equilibrium point, that point of balance,

740
00:45:42,174 --> 00:45:43,274
is not always the same.

741
00:45:43,714 --> 00:45:46,155
It is not always that you want an even balance

742
00:45:46,556 --> 00:45:48,076
between all of these different departments.

743
00:45:48,456 --> 00:45:50,577
But that balance and that equilibrium point shifts

744
00:45:51,137 --> 00:45:52,158
over the course of production.

745
00:45:52,758 --> 00:45:55,219
And you need to carefully maintain that and nurture that

746
00:45:55,839 --> 00:45:59,081
to help that spark grow into the kind of roaring flame

747
00:45:59,101 --> 00:45:59,701
that you want it to be.

748
00:46:00,641 --> 00:46:04,523
And really for me, looking back, that's my key takeaway.

749
00:46:06,397 --> 00:46:12,862
In conception, we had a very unbalanced process massively weighted towards, you know, innovation

750
00:46:13,543 --> 00:46:19,008
and protecting innovation and making that innovation as rapid and as effective as it

751
00:46:19,028 --> 00:46:23,672
could be. And it was incredibly effective. And I can't stress that enough. This is a process I

752
00:46:23,712 --> 00:46:30,618
would love to see other companies and other groups replicate because it was some of the most fulfilling.

753
00:46:32,830 --> 00:46:35,591
game development experience I've ever had in my career,

754
00:46:35,731 --> 00:46:37,952
and many people on the team, I think, would attest to that.

755
00:46:38,752 --> 00:46:40,953
And we've already started to see some experiments

756
00:46:41,373 --> 00:46:42,414
replicating that elsewhere,

757
00:46:42,534 --> 00:46:43,794
and it's been incredibly effective.

758
00:46:45,215 --> 00:46:46,635
But moving into pre-production,

759
00:46:46,995 --> 00:46:49,416
we made the mistake of just trying to keep going,

760
00:46:49,496 --> 00:46:50,697
trying to scale that process up.

761
00:46:51,577 --> 00:46:53,157
And we should have still kept...

762
00:46:54,913 --> 00:46:58,435
That balance on the side of innovation, it's still important to add that depth,

763
00:46:58,875 --> 00:47:00,376
but we had to start to tip the scales.

764
00:47:00,396 --> 00:47:04,739
We had to start to add some of that structure to make it work.

765
00:47:06,180 --> 00:47:07,680
And then, you know, moving into production,

766
00:47:09,181 --> 00:47:12,803
we had to find our new equilibrium point, our new balance point.

767
00:47:13,820 --> 00:47:17,162
And that's going to look different for everyone, you know, the path to get there,

768
00:47:18,382 --> 00:47:24,465
the path to adjust that new equilibrium. For us, it meant really creating the structure

769
00:47:24,906 --> 00:47:28,448
of having regular venues for healthy conflict,

770
00:47:31,809 --> 00:47:32,070
for...

771
00:47:33,310 --> 00:47:35,011
You know, venues where people could challenge.

772
00:47:35,191 --> 00:47:38,914
So, you know, we had creative briefs with a feature at an early level.

773
00:47:38,934 --> 00:47:41,235
So kind of a high level presentation overview of the feature,

774
00:47:41,595 --> 00:47:44,957
bringing in all the stakeholders who could say, OK, you know,

775
00:47:44,977 --> 00:47:47,939
I want to raise a flag about this. This is a warning.

776
00:47:48,319 --> 00:47:50,461
You know, then taking that into FSOs.

777
00:47:50,481 --> 00:47:52,422
This is very Ubisoft specific thing, but essentially a much,

778
00:47:52,502 --> 00:47:55,364
much more specific description of that feature.

779
00:47:55,764 --> 00:47:58,626
Again, with a forum for challenge and debate discussion.

780
00:48:00,067 --> 00:48:05,453
Our meetings became very much about making sure that anyone could add points for discussion.

781
00:48:06,274 --> 00:48:09,458
They weren't just top-down, me saying, here's the agenda.

782
00:48:09,879 --> 00:48:13,924
We built the agenda collaboratively, and we made sure that there were venues for everyone

783
00:48:14,344 --> 00:48:15,466
to discuss and argue.

784
00:48:15,886 --> 00:48:17,548
And we encouraged that healthy conflict.

785
00:48:19,534 --> 00:48:21,896
On the production side, we really shifted focus to velocity

786
00:48:22,216 --> 00:48:24,758
to better understand how we were tracking towards our scope.

787
00:48:25,679 --> 00:48:27,480
We used playtest and external validation

788
00:48:27,520 --> 00:48:30,102
to understand our audience and what's resonating.

789
00:48:30,743 --> 00:48:33,605
And we really refocused in on our game pillars

790
00:48:34,266 --> 00:48:37,068
in order to use those as the razor to help prioritize

791
00:48:37,168 --> 00:48:38,349
and focus on what's important.

792
00:48:38,909 --> 00:48:42,572
And we realized that only through focusing on these things

793
00:48:43,553 --> 00:48:45,955
could we protect these things and actually make them

794
00:48:47,556 --> 00:48:53,801
flourish in the game. For us, those pillars were of course this modular toy, you know,

795
00:48:53,821 --> 00:48:59,625
this instant connection, this magical moment that makes kids' eyes light up and their jaws drop.

796
00:49:01,887 --> 00:49:06,991
The creative combat that this instant swapping and connection empowers you to do in game,

797
00:49:07,471 --> 00:49:12,755
this creative problem solving where you get into a challenge and there's no right or wrong

798
00:49:12,855 --> 00:49:16,658
answer but you have to experiment and figure out how to adapt to take on that challenge.

799
00:49:18,276 --> 00:49:24,641
And this incredible, living, dynamic world that makes it for no two players having the

800
00:49:24,681 --> 00:49:27,343
same story, no two players having the same journey.

801
00:49:29,424 --> 00:49:34,588
Now we're still active in development, and I need to give a huge shout out to our team

802
00:49:34,708 --> 00:49:40,573
back in Toronto, who are still working very, very hard to bring everything to life.

803
00:49:41,290 --> 00:49:46,052
completely together and wrap it up. I'm super, super excited about the game. I'm super excited

804
00:49:46,092 --> 00:49:51,695
for you all to see more about it over the coming months. I can't wait. So far we've

805
00:49:51,715 --> 00:49:55,636
only given a little glimpse at E3, and I can't wait for people to see what we've been up

806
00:49:55,676 --> 00:50:04,600
to. And, you know, I'd really stress two things. One, I would love to see other people

807
00:50:05,806 --> 00:50:11,047
Take advantage of the lessons that we learned in that incredibly effective conception process,

808
00:50:11,087 --> 00:50:16,768
and you know, process that was inspired from game jam culture,

809
00:50:16,808 --> 00:50:18,629
from game jam processes that we adapted,

810
00:50:19,489 --> 00:50:25,710
and to keep an eye on that balance between structure and innovation

811
00:50:26,570 --> 00:50:30,031
in order to help get through all of those phases of production.

812
00:50:32,231 --> 00:50:32,771
Thank you very much.

813
00:50:32,791 --> 00:50:34,172
That's the end of my presentation.

814
00:50:42,125 --> 00:50:44,166
Now, I think we've got time for a couple questions.

815
00:50:45,427 --> 00:50:47,388
First, I want to stress, please, please, please,

816
00:50:48,269 --> 00:50:49,750
this is my first GDC presentation.

817
00:50:51,591 --> 00:50:53,612
And I would really, really love it and appreciate it

818
00:50:54,133 --> 00:50:56,514
if you would go, once you get the email,

819
00:50:57,255 --> 00:50:58,816
if you'd go and fill in the feedback form,

820
00:50:59,416 --> 00:51:00,817
because I would love the feedback.

821
00:51:01,458 --> 00:51:01,938
Love your thoughts.

822
00:51:03,179 --> 00:51:03,639
Any questions?

823
00:51:04,780 --> 00:51:06,401
There are two microphones there and there.

824
00:51:08,197 --> 00:51:12,499
Hi, so in the conception phase you had this two week period that ended with three pitches.

825
00:51:13,280 --> 00:51:14,961
How many pitches did you actually end up making?

826
00:51:15,861 --> 00:51:20,384
So the conception phase, you're asking me to do math.

827
00:51:21,124 --> 00:51:26,287
Okay, so first of all, the first week ended in three pitches per person.

828
00:51:26,628 --> 00:51:28,309
So that changed as our team scaled up.

829
00:51:29,229 --> 00:51:32,611
So pitch wise, you know, initially I guess we were doing 24 pitches.

830
00:51:35,642 --> 00:51:39,486
Every two weeks, but our team started growing as we were expanding.

831
00:51:39,506 --> 00:51:45,213
So by the time we got to our actual green light pitch,

832
00:51:48,416 --> 00:51:54,118
Many, over 100 fleshed out, more than that, I don't know, 150, tons and tons and tons

833
00:51:54,478 --> 00:51:55,679
of game pitches.

834
00:51:56,859 --> 00:51:58,880
There's really like a treasure trove there, I'd love to go back to that.

835
00:51:59,560 --> 00:52:02,041
We built three prototypes every two weeks.

836
00:52:03,482 --> 00:52:09,845
So that math should be a little bit easier, so again, doing math.

837
00:52:11,245 --> 00:52:14,566
I think all in all, we probably had...

838
00:52:16,901 --> 00:52:20,064
I don't know, 15, 16 different prototypes.

839
00:52:20,084 --> 00:52:23,828
That's not divisible by three, so it's almost not the real number, but somewhere in that

840
00:52:23,848 --> 00:52:24,208
ballpark.

841
00:52:26,030 --> 00:52:27,051
Hi, thanks for the presentation.

842
00:52:27,251 --> 00:52:28,232
You're welcome.

843
00:52:29,334 --> 00:52:34,779
So I'm wondering if during the process where you were pairing people up or putting them

844
00:52:34,799 --> 00:52:39,083
into the groups of four, did it really matter what disciplines you paired together or did

845
00:52:39,123 --> 00:52:39,964
you mix that up every time?

846
00:52:41,090 --> 00:52:45,973
So this is one of the areas where we actually, James and I actually put some design and thought into that.

847
00:52:47,174 --> 00:52:50,397
We would make sure to rotate so that people weren't paired up with the same people.

848
00:52:50,857 --> 00:52:52,739
Obviously we'd have a chance to go through.

849
00:52:53,879 --> 00:52:57,202
But we would try to pair people up where...

850
00:52:58,427 --> 00:53:03,370
One of the things we were most conscious of was one person steering or dominating that conversation too much.

851
00:53:03,810 --> 00:53:08,913
So we would try to pair more introverted or quieter people together in some cases,

852
00:53:10,134 --> 00:53:17,178
especially early on in the project, and, you know, more extroverted, loud people together who could play off each other's energies.

853
00:53:18,859 --> 00:53:24,463
That changed over the course of our production because as everyone started prototyping together,

854
00:53:24,843 --> 00:53:30,587
working very close in these intense things, building, pitching, everyone became much more

855
00:53:30,647 --> 00:53:34,930
comfortable working with each other and you know towards the end we had to be far less concerned

856
00:53:34,950 --> 00:53:38,973
about that and you know we were able to just rotate through people that hadn't worked together yet.

857
00:53:40,072 --> 00:53:40,872
Thanks.

858
00:53:41,533 --> 00:53:44,595
And also I noticed you had some AR pitches during the process.

859
00:53:44,615 --> 00:53:44,715
Sure.

860
00:53:44,976 --> 00:53:46,697
Was there ever an AR version of this game?

861
00:53:46,717 --> 00:53:48,779
You know, you see the keyboard placement stuff.

862
00:53:49,059 --> 00:53:49,799
That would be awesome.

863
00:53:50,940 --> 00:53:52,382
No, but it would be awesome.

864
00:53:54,803 --> 00:53:57,145
Just a small logistical question,

865
00:53:57,165 --> 00:53:59,808
because I also make games that are designed for kids.

866
00:54:00,968 --> 00:54:03,771
How did you find the kids for play testing?

867
00:54:03,871 --> 00:54:05,312
I've Googled this repeatedly, and I

868
00:54:05,352 --> 00:54:08,394
think the only result is I'm probably on some watch lists.

869
00:54:11,899 --> 00:54:17,545
We work with a wonderful user research team at Ubisoft and at Ubisoft Toronto,

870
00:54:17,906 --> 00:54:20,849
so I feel quite lucky to have a bunch of experts that can help guide us through that.

871
00:54:22,952 --> 00:54:26,696
We've done a lot of playtesting with kids and we continue to do regular playtesting with kids.

872
00:54:27,868 --> 00:54:33,851
I think it is wonderful to see really raw, unfiltered thoughts and reactions.

873
00:54:35,131 --> 00:54:38,853
Sometimes we ask people for scores on playtests of like, what do you think of the game?

874
00:54:38,933 --> 00:54:39,354
One to five.

875
00:54:40,054 --> 00:54:43,656
And we found kids are useless at giving scores.

876
00:54:44,776 --> 00:54:46,817
They are wonderful to learn usability lessons.

877
00:54:46,857 --> 00:54:50,099
They're wonderful to, you know, actually watch their reactions and see.

878
00:54:50,739 --> 00:54:52,260
But you know, we've had some...

879
00:54:53,201 --> 00:54:56,125
Playtests where, you know, the build is broken and there's some horrible glitch

880
00:54:56,165 --> 00:54:59,130
and you just see this kid banging their head against a problem and not understanding it.

881
00:55:00,092 --> 00:55:01,855
And, like, they look like they're going to start crying.

882
00:55:02,796 --> 00:55:05,421
And then we're like, what did you think of the game? And they're like, 5 out of 5! It was amazing!

883
00:55:05,441 --> 00:55:06,563
And we're like, okay.

884
00:55:07,535 --> 00:55:09,417
You're just excited because you're coming to test a video game.

885
00:55:09,898 --> 00:55:15,024
So you have to be a little skeptical and take any scores with a grain of salt.

886
00:55:15,524 --> 00:55:16,626
But I think there's immense value.

887
00:55:16,646 --> 00:55:18,868
There's always immense value in watching people

888
00:55:18,928 --> 00:55:23,454
from whatever target demo your game is targeting really play your game.

889
00:55:23,554 --> 00:55:25,056
It's a very, very humbling experience.

890
00:55:26,077 --> 00:55:26,217
Cool.

891
00:55:26,698 --> 00:55:26,878
Thanks.

892
00:55:28,750 --> 00:55:33,333
With the amount of ideas that you were asking your team to come up with during the brainstorming

893
00:55:33,373 --> 00:55:35,895
phase, did you run into a lot of creative burnout?

894
00:55:36,135 --> 00:55:37,796
And if so, how did you manage that?

895
00:55:38,777 --> 00:55:39,457
It's a great question.

896
00:55:40,278 --> 00:55:42,619
It is a really intense process.

897
00:55:43,840 --> 00:55:45,461
You know, the mental drain...

898
00:55:46,633 --> 00:55:51,936
that you get from, you know, you are really pushing yourself to go to the end of like

899
00:55:52,117 --> 00:55:55,679
whatever the heck, you know, after a week of doing this and generating these pitches

900
00:55:55,719 --> 00:56:00,662
and giving these pitches, you know, many people on our team, you know, was cross-disciplined,

901
00:56:00,682 --> 00:56:06,166
many people weren't that comfortable going up and presenting and that was a draining process.

902
00:56:06,946 --> 00:56:08,868
The key for us was that weekend.

903
00:56:09,800 --> 00:56:12,768
You know, the key for us, and that's a big part of why we split it up like that,

904
00:56:13,249 --> 00:56:17,961
was having that first week super intense, all these ideas are coming out.

905
00:56:19,522 --> 00:56:23,665
You'd pitch on Thursday, which was good, because that gave you a bit more time.

906
00:56:24,025 --> 00:56:27,408
You'd pitch on Thursday, come in on Friday, okay, pressure's off a little bit.

907
00:56:27,608 --> 00:56:29,830
You're not generating ideas. Now you're sitting with a team,

908
00:56:29,850 --> 00:56:31,732
and you're trying to figure out, how the heck can we prototype this?

909
00:56:32,572 --> 00:56:35,655
But that's more about people leveraging their experience, their skill set,

910
00:56:35,675 --> 00:56:37,877
saying, oh, I know how to do this, I could do that, I could, you know.

911
00:56:38,457 --> 00:56:40,078
It's very fun, it's very engaging.

912
00:56:40,659 --> 00:56:44,902
But then having that weekend to just go, let things simmer in your head for a bit.

913
00:56:45,743 --> 00:56:49,867
Calm down, and then be ready to go the next week with intense brainstorming.

914
00:56:50,828 --> 00:56:52,869
You know, it's kind of like participating in a game jam,

915
00:56:53,810 --> 00:56:55,892
but you need those gaps, you need those breaks in between.

916
00:56:56,713 --> 00:56:56,913
Thanks.

917
00:56:56,933 --> 00:56:57,634
You're welcome.

918
00:56:58,695 --> 00:57:01,437
Knowing how well your small prototyping group worked,

919
00:57:01,537 --> 00:57:04,720
would you say there's still value in doing studio-wide game jams?

920
00:57:07,326 --> 00:57:09,667
So we've also experimented with studio-wide game gems

921
00:57:10,887 --> 00:57:13,809
at both at UbiToronto and other studios that I've been at.

922
00:57:14,489 --> 00:57:17,090
I think they are very, very fun.

923
00:57:17,110 --> 00:57:18,451
I think they're a great retention tool.

924
00:57:18,491 --> 00:57:20,972
I think they're something very motivating for employees.

925
00:57:21,773 --> 00:57:22,873
I think one of the challenges is

926
00:57:27,830 --> 00:57:30,252
They don't necessarily have the right venue

927
00:57:30,313 --> 00:57:32,274
to turn into something real,

928
00:57:32,755 --> 00:57:34,476
to turn into something that you can really leverage.

929
00:57:35,217 --> 00:57:36,598
There's companies that have done that really well.

930
00:57:36,778 --> 00:57:39,400
I know Bethesda, you know, they tend to do game jams

931
00:57:39,681 --> 00:57:41,943
of how could you add a feature onto our existing game?

932
00:57:42,583 --> 00:57:45,266
But typically, the constraints of a game jam,

933
00:57:45,286 --> 00:57:46,827
you know, where you're doing everything in a week

934
00:57:46,847 --> 00:57:48,088
or you're doing everything in two days,

935
00:57:48,648 --> 00:57:51,111
limits you to creating kind of little arcade-y mini games,

936
00:57:51,451 --> 00:57:53,553
which are super fun, but isn't necessarily something

937
00:57:53,593 --> 00:57:54,694
that Ubisoft is gonna be like.

938
00:57:55,174 --> 00:57:55,934
